<li id="cite_note-Barroso-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Barroso_2-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREF.5B.5BJos.C3.A9_Manuel_Barroso.5D.5D.2C_11th_.5B.5BPresident_of_the_European_Commission.5D.5D"><a href="/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Manuel_Barroso" title="José Manuel Barroso">José Manuel Barroso</a>, 11th <a href="/wiki/President_of_the_European_Commission" title="President of the European Commission">President of the European Commission</a> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2006-11-28"><a href="/wiki/November_28" title="November 28">28 November</a> <a href="/wiki/2006" title="2006">2006</a></span>). <a href="http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=SPEECH/06/756&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=1&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en" class="external text" title="http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=SPEECH/06/756&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=1&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en" rel="nofollow">"The Scottish enlightenment and the challenges for Europe in the 21st century; climate change and energy"</a> (<a href="/wiki/Html" title="Html" class="mw-redirect">html</a>). <i>Enlightenment Lecture Series, <a href="/wiki/University_of_Edinburgh" title="University of Edinburgh">Edinburgh University</a></i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=SPEECH/06/756&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=1&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en" class="external free" title="http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=SPEECH/06/756&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=1&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en" rel="nofollow">http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=SPEECH/06/756&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=1&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en</a></span>.  "I will try to show why Voltaire was right when he said: 'Nous nous tournons vers l’Écosse pour trouver toutes nos idées sur la civilisation' [we look to Scotland for all our ideas on civilisation]."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=The+Scottish+enlightenment+and+the+challenges+for+Europe+in+the+21st+century%3B+climate+change+and+energy&amp;rft.atitle=Enlightenment+Lecture+Series%2C+%5B%5BUniversity+of+Edinburgh%7CEdinburgh+University%5D%5D&amp;rft.aulast=%5B%5BJos%C3%A9+Manuel+Barroso%5D%5D%2C+11th+%5B%5BPresident+of+the+European+Commission%5D%5D&amp;rft.au=%5B%5BJos%C3%A9+Manuel+Barroso%5D%5D%2C+11th+%5B%5BPresident+of+the+European+Commission%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=%5B%5B28+November%5D%5D+%5B%5B2006%5D%5D&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Feuropa.eu%2Frapid%2FpressReleasesAction.do%3Freference%3DSPEECH%2F06%2F756%26format%3DHTML%26aged%3D1%26language%3DEN%26guiLanguage%3Den&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Scottish_Enlightenment"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-RSE_Scotsman_Voltaire_quote-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-RSE_Scotsman_Voltaire_quote_3-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.royalsoced.org.uk/international/potocnik.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.royalsoced.org.uk/international/potocnik.htm" rel="nofollow">"Visiting The Royal Society of Edinburgh…"</a> (<a href="/wiki/Html" title="Html" class="mw-redirect">html</a>). <i><a href="/wiki/Royal_Society_of_Edinburgh" title="Royal Society of Edinburgh">Royal Society of Edinburgh</a>. First published in</i> <a href="/wiki/The_Scotsman" title="The Scotsman">The Scotsman</a> <i>Saturday 4 June 2005</i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.royalsoced.org.uk/international/potocnik.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.royalsoced.org.uk/international/potocnik.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.royalsoced.org.uk/international/potocnik.htm</a></span>.  "Scotland has a proud heritage of science, research, invention and innovation, and can lay claim to some of the greatest minds and greatest discoveries since Voltaire wrote those words 250 years ago."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Visiting+The+Royal+Society+of+Edinburgh%E2%80%A6&amp;rft.atitle=%5B%5BRoyal+Society+of+Edinburgh%5D%5D.+First+published+in+%27%27%5B%5BThe+Scotsman%5D%5D%27%27+Saturday+4+June+2005&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.royalsoced.org.uk%2Finternational%2Fpotocnik.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Scottish_Enlightenment"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Denby-4">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Denby_4-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Denby_4-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Denby_4-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Denby_4-3" title=""><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREF.5B.5BDavid_Denby_.28film_critic.29.7CDavid_Denby.5D.5D"><a href="/wiki/David_Denby_(film_critic)" title="David Denby (film critic)">David Denby</a> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2004-10-11"><a href="/wiki/October_11" title="October 11">11 October</a> <a href="/wiki/2004" title="2004">2004</a></span>). <a href="http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2004/10/11/041011crat_atlarge" class="external text" title="http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2004/10/11/041011crat_atlarge" rel="nofollow">"Northern Lights: How modern life emerged from eighteenth-century Edinburgh"</a> (<a href="/wiki/Html" title="Html" class="mw-redirect">html</a>). <i><a href="/wiki/The_New_Yorker" title="The New Yorker">The New Yorker</a></i>. Review of <a href="/wiki/James_Buchan" title="James Buchan">James Buchan</a>'s <i>Crowded With Genius: Edinburgh's Moment of the Mind (Capital of the Mind: Edinburgh</i> in the <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">UK</a>) <a href="/wiki/HarperCollins" title="HarperCollins">HarperCollins</a>, 2003. Hardcover: <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0060558881" class="internal">ISBN 0-06-055888-1</a>, <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780060558888" class="internal">ISBN 978-0060558888</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2004/10/11/041011crat_atlarge" class="external free" title="http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2004/10/11/041011crat_atlarge" rel="nofollow">http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2004/10/11/041011crat_atlarge</a></span>.  "The fountainhead was <a href="/wiki/Francis_Hutcheson" title="Francis Hutcheson">Francis Hutcheson</a>, a kind of pan-Enlightenment figure who, from 1729 until his death in 1746, held the chair in <a href="/wiki/Moral_philosophy" title="Moral philosophy" class="mw-redirect">moral philosophy</a> at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Glasgow" title="University of Glasgow">University of Glasgow</a>, where he broke with tradition by lecturing in <a href="/wiki/English_language" title="English language">English</a> in addition to the common lecturing language of the time, <a href="/wiki/Latin_language" title="Latin language" class="mw-redirect">Latin</a>. Hutcheson, a frequent visitor to <a href="/wiki/Edinburgh" title="Edinburgh">Edinburgh</a>, was <a href="/wiki/Adam_Smith" title="Adam Smith">Adam Smith</a>’s teacher and he encouraged <a href="/wiki/David_Hume" title="David Hume">Hume</a>’s early efforts. He was suspicious of <a href="/wiki/Metaphysics" title="Metaphysics">metaphysics</a> or any claims not based on <a href="/wiki/Observation" title="Observation">observation</a> or <a href="/wiki/Experience" title="Experience">experience</a>. <a href="/wiki/Empiricism" title="Empiricism">Empiricism</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Inductive_reasoning" title="Inductive reasoning">inductive method</a> was the clarion call of the Scottish Enlightenment.<br />
The intellectual break with the past was drastic and seemingly irreversible. In recent years, scholars have traced the rudiments of modern psychology, anthropology, the earth sciences, and theories of civil society and liberal education to eighteenth-century Scotland."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Northern+Lights%3A+How+modern+life+emerged+from+eighteenth-century+Edinburgh&amp;rft.atitle=%5B%5BThe+New+Yorker%5D%5D&amp;rft.aulast=%5B%5BDavid+Denby+%28film+critic%29%7CDavid+Denby%5D%5D&amp;rft.au=%5B%5BDavid+Denby+%28film+critic%29%7CDavid+Denby%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=%5B%5B11+October%5D%5D+%5B%5B2004%5D%5D&amp;rft.pub=Review+of+%5B%5BJames+Buchan%5D%5D%27s+%27%27Crowded+With+Genius%3A+Edinburgh%27s+Moment+of+the+Mind++%28Capital+of+the+Mind%3A+Edinburgh%27%27+in+the+%5B%5BUnited+Kingdom%7CUK%5D%5D%29+%5B%5BHarperCollins%5D%5D%2C+2003.++Hardcover%3A+ISBN+0-06-055888-1%2C+ISBN+978-0060558888&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.newyorker.com%2Farchive%2F2004%2F10%2F11%2F041011crat_atlarge&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Scottish_Enlightenment"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Fry-5"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Fry_5-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFFry1992">Fry, Michael (1992). <i>Adam Smith's Legacy: His Place in the Development of Modern Economics</i>. <a href="/wiki/Paul_Samuelson" title="Paul Samuelson">Paul Samuelson</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lawrence_Klein" title="Lawrence Klein">Lawrence Klein</a>, <a href="/wiki/Franco_Modigliani" title="Franco Modigliani">Franco Modigliani</a>, <a href="/wiki/James_M._Buchanan" title="James M. Buchanan">James M. Buchanan</a>, <a href="/wiki/Maurice_Allais" title="Maurice Allais">Maurice Allais</a>, <a href="/wiki/Theodore_Schultz" title="Theodore Schultz">Theodore Schultz</a>, <a href="/wiki/Richard_Stone" title="Richard Stone">Richard Stone</a>, <a href="/wiki/James_Tobin" title="James Tobin">James Tobin</a>, <a href="/wiki/Wassily_Leontief" title="Wassily Leontief">Wassily Leontief</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jan_Tinbergen" title="Jan Tinbergen">Jan Tinbergen</a>. <a href="/wiki/Routledge" title="Routledge">Routledge</a>. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780415061643" class="internal">ISBN 978-0415061643</a>.  "<i>Adam Smith's Legacy</i> brings together ten <a href="/wiki/Nobel_Prize_in_Economics" title="Nobel Prize in Economics" class="mw-redirect">Nobel Laureates in Economics</a>, the greatest number since the prize was instituted in 1969. They explore themes as diverse as Smith's use of data, his attitude towards human capital, and his views on economic policy. Heirs to Smith and leaders of the discipline, the contributors also reflect upon the current state of economics, assessing the extent to which it measures up to the benchmark established by its founder."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Adam+Smith%27s+Legacy%3A+His+Place+in+the+Development+of+Modern+Economics&amp;rft.aulast=Fry&amp;rft.aufirst=Michael&amp;rft.au=Fry%2C+Michael&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BRoutledge%5D%5D&amp;rft.isbn=978-0415061643&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Scottish_Enlightenment"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Magnusson-6">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Magnusson_6-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Magnusson_6-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Magnusson_6-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Magnusson_6-3" title=""><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREF.5B.5BMagnus_Magnusson.5D.5D"><a href="/wiki/Magnus_Magnusson" title="Magnus Magnusson" class="mw-redirect">Magnus Magnusson</a> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2003-11-10"><a href="/wiki/November_10" title="November 10">10 November</a> <a href="/wiki/2003" title="2003">2003</a></span>). <a href="http://www.newstatesman.com/200311100040" class="external text" title="http://www.newstatesman.com/200311100040" rel="nofollow">"Northern lights"</a> (<a href="/wiki/Html" title="Html" class="mw-redirect">html</a>). <i><a href="/wiki/New_Statesman" title="New Statesman">New Statesman</a></i>. Review of <a href="/wiki/James_Buchan" title="James Buchan">James Buchan</a>'s <i>Capital of the Mind: Edinburgh (Crowded With Genius: Edinburgh's Moment of the Mind</i> in the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">U.S.</a>) <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">London</a>: <a href="/wiki/John_Murray_(publisher)" title="John Murray (publisher)">John Murray</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0719554462" class="internal">ISBN 0719554462</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.newstatesman.com/200311100040" class="external free" title="http://www.newstatesman.com/200311100040" rel="nofollow">http://www.newstatesman.com/200311100040</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Northern+lights&amp;rft.atitle=%5B%5BNew+Statesman%5D%5D&amp;rft.aulast=%5B%5BMagnus+Magnusson%5D%5D&amp;rft.au=%5B%5BMagnus+Magnusson%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=%5B%5B10+November%5D%5D+%5B%5B2003%5D%5D&amp;rft.pub=Review+of+%5B%5BJames+Buchan%5D%5D%27s+%27%27Capital+of+the+Mind%3A+Edinburgh++%28Crowded+With+Genius%3A+Edinburgh%27s+Moment+of+the+Mind%27%27+in+the+%5B%5BUnited+States%7CU.S.%5D%5D%29+%5B%5BLondon%5D%5D%3A+%5B%5BJohn+Murray+%28publisher%29%7CJohn+Murray%5D%5D+ISBN+0719554462&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.newstatesman.com%2F200311100040&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Scottish_Enlightenment"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Repcheck-7">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Repcheck_7-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Repcheck_7-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Repcheck_7-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFRepcheck2003">Repcheck, Jack (2003). "Chapter 7: The Athens of the North" (in English). <i>The Man Who Found Time: James Hutton and the Discovery of the Earth's Antiquity</i>. <a href="/wiki/Cambridge,_Massachusetts" title="Cambridge, Massachusetts">Cambridge, Massachusetts</a>: <a href="/wiki/Basic_Books" title="Basic Books">Basic Books</a>, <a href="http://www.perseusbooksgroup.com/perseus/home.jsp" class="external text" title="http://www.perseusbooksgroup.com/perseus/home.jsp" rel="nofollow">The Perseus Books Group</a>. pp.&#160;117–143. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/073820692X" class="internal">ISBN 0-7382-0692-X</a>.  "Onto the list should also be added two men who never lived in <a href="/wiki/Edinburgh" title="Edinburgh">Edinburgh</a> but who visited and maintained an active correspondence with the scholars there: <a href="/wiki/Benjamin_Franklin" title="Benjamin Franklin">Ben Franklin</a> (1706-1790), the statesman and talented <a href="/wiki/Polymath" title="Polymath">polymath</a> who discovered <a href="/wiki/Electricity" title="Electricity">electricity</a>; and <a href="/wiki/Erasmus_Darwin" title="Erasmus Darwin">Erasmus Darwin</a> (1731-1802), <a href="/wiki/Charles_Darwin" title="Charles Darwin">Charles Darwin</a>'s grandfather and the author of a precursor <a href="/wiki/Theory" title="Theory">theory</a> of <a href="/wiki/Evolution" title="Evolution">evolution</a>."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Chapter+7%3A+The+Athens+of+the+North&amp;rft.atitle=The+Man+Who+Found+Time%3A+James+Hutton+and+the+Discovery+of+the+Earth%27s+Antiquity&amp;rft.aulast=Repcheck&amp;rft.aufirst=Jack&amp;rft.au=Repcheck%2C+Jack&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3B117%E2%80%93143&amp;rft.place=%5B%5BCambridge%2C+Massachusetts%5D%5D&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BBasic+Books%5D%5D%2C+%5Bhttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.perseusbooksgroup.com%2Fperseus%2Fhome.jsp+The+Perseus+Books+Group%5D&amp;rft.isbn=0-7382-0692-X&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Scottish_Enlightenment"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Manning-8">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Manning_8-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Manning_8-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFPhillip_Manning">Phillip Manning (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2003-12-28"><a href="/wiki/December_28" title="December 28">28 December</a> <a href="/wiki/2003" title="2003">2003</a></span>). <a href="http://www.scibooks.org/manwhofoundtime.html" class="external text" title="http://www.scibooks.org/manwhofoundtime.html" rel="nofollow">"A Toast To Times Past"</a> (<a href="/wiki/Html" title="Html" class="mw-redirect">html</a>). <i><a href="/wiki/Chapel_Hill,_North_Carolina" title="Chapel Hill, North Carolina">Chapel Hill</a> News</i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.scibooks.org/manwhofoundtime.html" class="external free" title="http://www.scibooks.org/manwhofoundtime.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.scibooks.org/manwhofoundtime.html</a></span>.  "Burns penned the song [<a href="/wiki/Auld_Lang_Syne" title="Auld Lang Syne">Auld Lang Syne</a>] in 1788 during the intellectual flowering known as the Scottish Enlightenment. Burns was part of a convivial group in Edinburgh whose writing and thinking produced the Enlightenment. One of the most original thinkers in that group, the man whose work would stimulate <a href="/wiki/Charles_Darwin" title="Charles Darwin">Charles Darwin</a>’s ideas about <a href="/wiki/Evolution" title="Evolution">evolution</a>, was a well-to-do gentleman farmer named <a href="/wiki/James_Hutton" title="James Hutton">James Hutton</a>. He discovered the immensity of our past, the days gone by that Burns wrote about so eloquently."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=A+Toast+To+Times+Past&amp;rft.atitle=%5B%5BChapel+Hill%2C+North+Carolina%7CChapel+Hill%5D%5D+News&amp;rft.aulast=Phillip+Manning&amp;rft.au=Phillip+Manning&amp;rft.date=%5B%5B28+December%5D%5D+%5B%5B2003%5D%5D&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.scibooks.org%2Fmanwhofoundtime.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Scottish_Enlightenment"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-FletcherCambridgePress-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FletcherCambridgePress_9-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREF.5B.5BCambridge_University_Press.5D.5D"><a href="/wiki/Cambridge_University_Press" title="Cambridge University Press">Cambridge University Press</a>. <a href="http://www.cambridge.org/us/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780521439947" class="external text" title="http://www.cambridge.org/us/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780521439947" rel="nofollow">"Andrew Fletcher: Political Works"</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.cambridge.org/us/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780521439947" class="external free" title="http://www.cambridge.org/us/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780521439947" rel="nofollow">http://www.cambridge.org/us/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780521439947</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Andrew+Fletcher%3A+Political+Works&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=%5B%5BCambridge+University+Press%5D%5D&amp;rft.au=%5B%5BCambridge+University+Press%5D%5D&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cambridge.org%2Fus%2Fcatalogue%2Fcatalogue.asp%3Fisbn%3D9780521439947&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Scottish_Enlightenment"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-David_Allan-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-David_Allan_10-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFDr_David_Allan">Dr David Allan. <a href="http://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/academic/history/scothist/hons/4111.shtml" class="external text" title="http://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/academic/history/scothist/hons/4111.shtml" rel="nofollow">"A Hotbed of Genius: Culture and Society in the Scottish Enlightenment"</a> (<a href="/wiki/Html" title="Html" class="mw-redirect">html</a>). <i><a href="/wiki/University_of_St_Andrews" title="University of St Andrews">University of St Andrews</a></i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/academic/history/scothist/hons/4111.shtml" class="external free" title="http://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/academic/history/scothist/hons/4111.shtml" rel="nofollow">http://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/academic/history/scothist/hons/4111.shtml</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=A+Hotbed+of+Genius%3A+Culture+and+Society+in+the+Scottish+Enlightenment&amp;rft.atitle=%5B%5BUniversity+of+St+Andrews%5D%5D&amp;rft.aulast=Dr+David+Allan&amp;rft.au=Dr+David+Allan&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.st-andrews.ac.uk%2Facademic%2Fhistory%2Fscothist%2Fhons%2F4111.shtml&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Scottish_Enlightenment"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ol>
</div>
